         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Museum, Auckland, N.Z, ¶ August 2d 1881 ¶ My Dear Baron Mueller, ¶  ¶ I trust you will excuse me for asking your assistance in the following matter. In vol 5 of the "Flora Australiensis" a species of ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">81.08.02</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Thomas Cheeseman</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M1, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS annotation by M: 'Answ 16/8/81'. Letter not found.</p>
               </note>Museum, Auckland, N.Z,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">August 2d 1881</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My Dear Baron Mueller,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I trust you will excuse me for asking your assistance in the following matter. In vol 5 of the "Flora Australiensis" a species of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Scleranthus</hi>
               </seg> is described under the name of S. <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">mniaroides</hi>
               </seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham (1863-78), vol. 5, <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>p. 259.</p>
               </note> which seems to differ chiefly from S. <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">biflorus</hi>
               </seg> in the flowers being solitary, and in the smaller size of all its parts. Now I have gathered in the mountains of the South Island a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Scleranthus</hi>
               </seg> which I have often thought might be this species; and which certainly looks very different to any of the ordinary states of S. <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">biflorus</hi>
               </seg>. I have ventured to send you a specimen, and should feel extremely obliged if you would compare it with the Australian plant and let me know the result. I also enclose a specimen of a lax-growing form of S. biflorus which is not uncommon in the South Island.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You will remember my sending you specimens of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Poranthera</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">microphylla</hi>
               </seg> from the Nelson district.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See T. Cheeseman to M, 4 March 1878 (in this edition as 78-03-04c).</p>
               </note> Last summer I gathered a second species at an altitude of 5000 ft on Mt Arthur, in the N. W. of Nelson. It was evidently quite distinct from any of the Australian species, and I have consequently described it under the name of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">P. alpina</hi>
               </seg>. It is interesting to find another of the purely Australian genera to be represented in New Zealand. Sir W. J. Hooker, to whom I forwarded specimens, agrees with me in thinking the species to be perfectly distinct.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Cheeseman presumably means Joseph Hooker.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours very truly</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>T. F. Cheeseman</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Baron F von Mueller, FRS.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>&amp;c<space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>&amp;c<space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>&amp;c</p>
